1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,780
Before we start implementing our model,

2

00:00:02,780  -->  00:00:06,140
let's talk about how to prepare training data for it.

3

00:00:06,140  -->  00:00:08,860
We'll first need to implement a tokenizer,

4

00:00:08,860  -->  00:00:12,720
which will allow us to convert text into token IDs,

5

00:00:12,720  -->  00:00:17,000
and we will look into how to do this in one of the next demos.

6

00:00:17,000  -->  00:00:20,820
We'll also need to prepare a training dataset in a way

7

00:00:20,820  -->  00:00:25,220
that will allow us to train our model to predict next token.

8

00:00:25,220  -->  00:00:30,260
Remember that the goal of our model is to predict the next token.

9

00:00:30,260  -->  00:00:33,880
Giving a single part of an input dataset,

10

00:00:33,880  -->  00:00:39,200
we can generate several prediction tasks for our model at once.

11

00:00:39,200  -->  00:00:41,840
Let's say we have a phrase.

12

00:00:41,840  -->  00:00:46,600
The core innovation of transformers is the attention.

13

00:00:46,710  -->  00:00:49,850
From this phrase, given the word the,

14

00:00:49,850  -->  00:00:52,660
we want our model to predict core.

15

00:00:52,660  -->  00:00:54,950
Given the that core,

16

00:00:54,950  -->  00:00:56,990
we wanted to predict innovation,

17

00:00:56,990  -->  00:01:01,550
and so on until given all input tokens except the last one,

18

00:01:01,550  -->  00:01:04,630
we want our model to predict the last word.

19

00:01:04,630  -->  00:01:08,770
The way we will represent this in our dataset is that inputs and

20

00:01:08,770  -->  00:01:13,565
targets will be part of the same phrase but shifted by one position.

21

00:01:13,565  -->  00:01:17,970
Of course, our model won't see words or tokens themselves.

22

00:01:17,970  -->  00:01:22,250
Instead, we will convert tokens into token IDs.

23

00:01:22,250  -->  00:01:25,455
Our training examples will look like this.

24

00:01:25,455  -->  00:01:27,500
But when visualizing it,

25

00:01:27,500  -->  00:01:31,760
it is easier to talk about the words rather than token IDs.

26

00:01:31,760  -->  00:01:35,120
Now, when we perform a single training iteration,

27

00:01:35,120  -->  00:01:38,960
we don't just send a single training example.

28

00:01:39,960  -->  00:01:47,300
We will instead pick multiple random training examples and run our model on a set,

29

00:01:47,300  -->  00:01:50,580
or, as it is usually called a training batch.

30

00:01:50,580  -->  00:01:55,480
This allows to better utilize GPU resources during training.

31

00:01:55,480  -->  00:01:57,240
In the next few videos,

32

00:01:57,240  -->  00:02:01,270
we will talk about how to do this in Python.
